					<div class="post">
				<h3>Re: So far...</h3>
				<div class="date">Posted: <strong>Tue May 19, 2020 3:07 pm</strong></div>
				<div class="author">by <strong>SteveC</strong></div>
				<div class="content">Thanks Simon, you prompted me to post my code in 'Firmware Stuff'.<br>
<br>
I thought of asking Justine if I could contribute on GitHub but I fear I might end up breaking stuff. I already use a different FONA baud rate (9600) and a different hardware pin for FONA receive. The current code is great in that it does what it says, it's a working start, and the rotary dial code works well but it's not a strong foundation for development. Ideally we need a new parsing engine for FONA messages, like the method used by Mikal Hart for TinyGPS++ (where, if available, a character is 'fed' to a parsing engine once per iteration of the main loop). Sorry I digress, I can't do this on my own, even Mikal acknowledges help.<br>
<br>
I've been getting my displays from here, surprisingly fast:<br>
<a href="https://www.aliexpress.com/item/32960168615.html" class="postlink">https://www.aliexpress.com/item/32960168615.html</a><br>
As far as I can tell the Waveshare displays are identical to the Dalian Good Display one but come with stickers on the back - don't try to remove them!<br>
<br>
Tips: if you push the end of the display along it's length you can bend it further. Use the absolute minimum epoxy possible, tape a 29mm wide L-shaped plastic guide to the back to help align the display before the epoxy sets... but we'll probably have to accept some artifacts, I call it character, the distressed look!<br>
<br>
Cheers</div>
			</div>
